copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351103206
Change-Id: Ifa9821e3dc1d4fd15c440da19a7e03d26daaa89e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/c4b65fb31409e3dbd0ad8a33423f86971cc27162"},{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

[{"sha":"026ba5b01344da2f43966367ab8922042933acb6","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"ensure context cancel is never nil

The context used for Stop is more appropriately tied to the lifetime of
the provisioner rather than a call to the ProvisionResource method. In
some cases Stop can be called before ProvisionResource, causing a panic
the provisioner.  Rather than adding nil checks to the CancelFunc call
for Stop, create a base context to use for cancellation with both Stop
and Close methods.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tokyo2006/terraform/commits/026ba5b01344da2f43966367ab8922042933acb6"},{"sha":"3e224df3794e9f21a015a749e7163f9be3896e64","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"destroy plan with provider config from data","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tokyo2006/terraform/commits/3e224df3794e9f21a015a749e7163f9be3896e64"},{"sha":"0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh state during a destroy plan

Because the destroy plan only creates the necessary changes for apply to
remove all the resources, it does no reading of resources or data
sources, leading to stale data in the state. In most cases this is not a
problem, but when a provider configuration is using resource values, the
provider may not be able to run correctly during apply. In prior
versions of terraform, the implicit refresh that happened during
`terraform destroy` would update the data sources and remove missing
resources from state as required.

The destroy plan graph has a minimal amount of information, so it is not
feasible to work the reading of resources into the operation without
completely replicating the normal plan graph, and updating the plan
graph and all destroy node implementation is also a considerable amount
of refactoring. Instead, we can run a normal plan which is used to
refresh the state before creating the destroy plan. This brings back
similar behavior to core versions prior to 0.14, and the refresh can
still be skipped using the `-refresh=false` cli flag.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tokyo2006/terraform/commits/0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1"},{"sha":"e614fb9aed597252e6ca18244ca779e0d61d3683","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh is expected for destroy

These tests were not previously running a refresh, and hence did not

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351196886
Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/huaxz1986/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"1a324f5c7249fbff56ed0b488d3cb20379a35d92","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Allow more of the internal checks to have open-source counterparts.

 * gtest includes will be flagged as errors
 * use of the error reporter without the wrapper macros will be an error.
 * assert can not be used (static_assert is ok).

[{"sha":"7d6a341cc2569f3323120462b4922e9703132ce9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/7d6a341cc2569f3323120462b4922e9703132ce9"}]

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

[{"sha":"3e224df3794e9f21a015a749e7163f9be3896e64","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"destroy plan with provider config from data","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/terraform/commits/3e224df3794e9f21a015a749e7163f9be3896e64"},{"sha":"0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh state during a destroy plan

Because the destroy plan only creates the necessary changes for apply to
remove all the resources, it does no reading of resources or data
sources, leading to stale data in the state. In most cases this is not a
problem, but when a provider configuration is using resource values, the
provider may not be able to run correctly during apply. In prior
versions of terraform, the implicit refresh that happened during
`terraform destroy` would update the data sources and remove missing
resources from state as required.

The destroy plan graph has a minimal amount of information, so it is not
feasible to work the reading of resources into the operation without
completely replicating the normal plan graph, and updating the plan
graph and all destroy node implementation is also a considerable amount
of refactoring. Instead, we can run a normal plan which is used to
refresh the state before creating the destroy plan. This brings back
similar behavior to core versions prior to 0.14, and the refresh can
still be skipped using the `-refresh=false` cli flag.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/terraform/commits/0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1"},{"sha":"e614fb9aed597252e6ca18244ca779e0d61d3683","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh is expected for destroy

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

* feat(kuma-cp) send custom strings in health checks

Introducing new field called `tcp` in HealthCheck resource, with
fields `send` and `receive`, which can be provided and will configure
envoy to send provided bytes during tcp health check and expecting
provided bytes in response. Field `receive` expect list of bytes as you
can specify multiple byte blocks. When checking the response,
“fuzzy” matching is performed such that each block must be found, and in
the order specified, but not necessarily contiguous.

More:
https://www.envoyproxy.io/docs/envoy/latest/configuration/upstream/cluster_manager/cluster_hc#config-cluster-manager-cluster-hc

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* feat(kuma-cp) http health checks

Introduced possibility to provide HTTP configuration for health checks,
which will send health checks as HTTP requests.

As internal traffic is mostly using HTTP 2, it's the default protocol
used when health checks are configured to use HTTP. To change that
behaviour you can use `http.use_http1` parameter and set it to true.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) regenerate protobufs for healthchecks

As in master landed PR with protobuf upgrade, I had to regenerate
protbuf related code for health checks, it also involved small changes
in health_check_configurer_test.go file.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) adress comments from CR + more

- Found nasty bug when provided `expectedStatuses` in your health check
  manifest it was generating wrong Int64Range as it should be half
  closed (`start` is inclusive and `end` is exclusive), so it was fixed,
  and the tests reflects this
- Changed some of the properties of the HealthCheck resource to the
  primitive ones (`string`s) and removed logic related to validation if
  the value is provided or empty
- As after protobuf upgrade when unmarshaling our manifests when
  provided empty slices they are becoming `nil`s
- Used `oneof` for `http`/`tcp` blocks in HealthCheck resource and
  removed validation logic which was checking if both of them were not
  provided at the same time

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351196886
Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"79c7e6e677d65979628353eaefe44170d3f2b4b0","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #45457 from rkuester:feature-micro-add-op-fill-pr3

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"79c7e6e677d65979628353eaefe44170d3f2b4b0","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #45457 from rkuester:feature-micro-add-op-fill-pr3

This pass clusters ops according to the policy specified by the pass options. The only currently supported option is 'oplist'. This option allows to specify the names of the ops that should be clustered when they form a simple def-use chain, that is, the next op is the only user of the previous op result. The pass identifies sequences of such ops and extracts them into clusters, represented by tf_device::ClusterOp.

This pass will be used to support flexibly policy in defining operations to be compiled in a single kernel for CPU code generation. The 'oplist' policy will be used to support user-guided fusion, where a specified sequence of operations is replaced by a single fused jitted kernel.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351196886
Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"091856315b2f1c9e968750ecccbade7d5aa4d7db","author":{"name":"A. [{"sha":"021fda922c9ee817d1ab433acc21a14c38835972","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/021fda922c9ee817d1ab433acc21a14c38835972"}]

Resolves https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/45536.

[{"sha":"3e224df3794e9f21a015a749e7163f9be3896e64","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"destroy plan with provider config from data","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/claytonbrown/terraform/commits/3e224df3794e9f21a015a749e7163f9be3896e64"},{"sha":"0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh state during a destroy plan

Because the destroy plan only creates the necessary changes for apply to
remove all the resources, it does no reading of resources or data
sources, leading to stale data in the state. In most cases this is not a
problem, but when a provider configuration is using resource values, the
provider may not be able to run correctly during apply. In prior
versions of terraform, the implicit refresh that happened during
`terraform destroy` would update the data sources and remove missing
resources from state as required.

The destroy plan graph has a minimal amount of information, so it is not
feasible to work the reading of resources into the operation without
completely replicating the normal plan graph, and updating the plan
graph and all destroy node implementation is also a considerable amount
of refactoring. Instead, we can run a normal plan which is used to
refresh the state before creating the destroy plan. This brings back
similar behavior to core versions prior to 0.14, and the refresh can
still be skipped using the `-refresh=false` cli flag.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/claytonbrown/terraform/commits/0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1"},{"sha":"e614fb9aed597252e6ca18244ca779e0d61d3683","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh is expected for destroy

These tests were not previously running a refresh, and hence did not

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

[{"sha":"3e224df3794e9f21a015a749e7163f9be3896e64","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"destroy plan with provider config from data","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/3e224df3794e9f21a015a749e7163f9be3896e64"},{"sha":"0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh state during a destroy plan

Because the destroy plan only creates the necessary changes for apply to
remove all the resources, it does no reading of resources or data
sources, leading to stale data in the state. In most cases this is not a
problem, but when a provider configuration is using resource values, the
provider may not be able to run correctly during apply. In prior
versions of terraform, the implicit refresh that happened during
`terraform destroy` would update the data sources and remove missing
resources from state as required.

The destroy plan graph has a minimal amount of information, so it is not
feasible to work the reading of resources into the operation without
completely replicating the normal plan graph, and updating the plan
graph and all destroy node implementation is also a considerable amount
of refactoring. Instead, we can run a normal plan which is used to
refresh the state before creating the destroy plan. This brings back
similar behavior to core versions prior to 0.14, and the refresh can
still be skipped using the `-refresh=false` cli flag.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1"},{"sha":"e614fb9aed597252e6ca18244ca779e0d61d3683","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh is expected for destroy

These tests were not previously running a refresh, and hence did not
expect the resources to be read.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/e614fb9aed597252e6ca18244ca779e0d61d3683"},{"sha":"fb2208a6d9f9927179475e808f87068e49b2a81f","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refactor context plan

Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"287ab9046604c277908969e20b7b4c0febe8b4ab","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"Return an error instead of crashing

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351103206
Change-Id: Ifa9821e3dc1d4fd15c440da19a7e03d26daaa89e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/c4b65fb31409e3dbd0ad8a33423f86971cc27162"},{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

Welcome to the v1.4.2 release of containerd!
------------------------------------------------------

The second patch release for containerd 1.4 includes multiple minor fixes
and updates.

Notable Updates

- Fix bug limiting the number of layers by default containerd/cri#1602

- Update default seccomp profile for pidfd containerd/containerd#4730

Windows

- Fix integer overflow on Windows containerd/containerd#4589

* feat(kuma-cp) send custom strings in health checks

Introducing new field called `tcp` in HealthCheck resource, with
fields `send` and `receive`, which can be provided and will configure
envoy to send provided bytes during tcp health check and expecting
provided bytes in response. Field `receive` expect list of bytes as you
can specify multiple byte blocks. When checking the response,
“fuzzy” matching is performed such that each block must be found, and in
the order specified, but not necessarily contiguous.

More:
https://www.envoyproxy.io/docs/envoy/latest/configuration/upstream/cluster_manager/cluster_hc#config-cluster-manager-cluster-hc

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* feat(kuma-cp) http health checks

Introduced possibility to provide HTTP configuration for health checks,
which will send health checks as HTTP requests.

As internal traffic is mostly using HTTP 2, it's the default protocol
used when health checks are configured to use HTTP. To change that
behaviour you can use `http.use_http1` parameter and set it to true.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) regenerate protobufs for healthchecks

As in master landed PR with protobuf upgrade, I had to regenerate
protbuf related code for health checks, it also involved small changes
in health_check_configurer_test.go file.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) adress comments from CR + more

- Found nasty bug when provided `expectedStatuses` in your health check
  manifest it was generating wrong Int64Range as it should be half
  closed (`start` is inclusive and `end` is exclusive), so it was fixed,
  and the tests reflects this
- Changed some of the properties of the HealthCheck resource to the
  primitive ones (`string`s) and removed logic related to validation if
  the value is provided or empty
- As after protobuf upgrade when unmarshaling our manifests when
  provided empty slices they are becoming `nil`s
- Used `oneof` for `http`/`tcp` blocks in HealthCheck resource and
  removed validation logic which was checking if both of them were not
  provided at the same time

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"79c7e6e677d65979628353eaefe44170d3f2b4b0","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #45457 from rkuester:feature-micro-add-op-fill-pr3

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351196886
Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"79c7e6e677d65979628353eaefe44170d3f2b4b0","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #45457 from rkuester:feature-micro-add-op-fill-pr3

Change-Id: I3442dd0f4d1e939787f4fb31c576f3a4368160bb","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rkuester/tensorflow/commits/94550574cdc0b0c61181d10d1df87eed60f4d7fa"},{"sha":"35fc7c9443f088d5c7551608c38750dc6deff8a4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Migrate convolution thunk emission to MLIR

- Map MLIR LHLO Conv operations to ConvolutionThunk.
- Refactor GetGpuConvConfig() to take in a conv descriptor, so that the same function
  can be used to emit a thunk from XLA HLO and MLIR representations.
- Change XlaConvLayoutsToStreamExecutorLayouts() to check shape<->layout
  compatibility instead of layout equality, since some XLA layouts with unit dimensions
   are not preserved in XLA HLO Shape -> MLIR -> XLA HLO Shape path.
- Note that window reversal is not yet representable in HLO/LHLO, so fall back to
   XLA HLO based thunk emission for that case.

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"3e224df3794e9f21a015a749e7163f9be3896e64","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"destroy plan with provider config from data","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/3e224df3794e9f21a015a749e7163f9be3896e64"},{"sha":"0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh state during a destroy plan

Because the destroy plan only creates the necessary changes for apply to
remove all the resources, it does no reading of resources or data
sources, leading to stale data in the state. In most cases this is not a
problem, but when a provider configuration is using resource values, the
provider may not be able to run correctly during apply. In prior
versions of terraform, the implicit refresh that happened during
`terraform destroy` would update the data sources and remove missing
resources from state as required.

The destroy plan graph has a minimal amount of information, so it is not
feasible to work the reading of resources into the operation without
completely replicating the normal plan graph, and updating the plan
graph and all destroy node implementation is also a considerable amount
of refactoring. Instead, we can run a normal plan which is used to
refresh the state before creating the destroy plan. This brings back
similar behavior to core versions prior to 0.14, and the refresh can
still be skipped using the `-refresh=false` cli flag.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1"},{"sha":"e614fb9aed597252e6ca18244ca779e0d61d3683","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh is expected for destroy

These tests were not previously running a refresh, and hence did not
expect the resources to be read.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/e614fb9aed597252e6ca18244ca779e0d61d3683"},{"sha":"fb2208a6d9f9927179475e808f87068e49b2a81f","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refactor context plan

Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351196886
Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"79c7e6e677d65979628353eaefe44170d3f2b4b0","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #45457 from rkuester:feature-micro-add-op-fill-pr3

Change-Id: Ifa9821e3dc1d4fd15c440da19a7e03d26daaa89e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/joshrose/tensorflow/commits/c4b65fb31409e3dbd0ad8a33423f86971cc27162"},{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

Because the destroy plan only creates the necessary changes for apply to
remove all the resources, it does no reading of resources or data
sources, leading to stale data in the state. In most cases this is not a
problem, but when a provider configuration is using resource values, the
provider may not be able to run correctly during apply. In prior
versions of terraform, the implicit refresh that happened during
`terraform destroy` would update the data sources and remove missing
resources from state as required.

The destroy plan graph has a minimal amount of information, so it is not
feasible to work the reading of resources into the operation without
completely replicating the normal plan graph, and updating the plan
graph and all destroy node implementation is also a considerable amount
of refactoring. Instead, we can run a normal plan which is used to
refresh the state before creating the destroy plan. This brings back
similar behavior to core versions prior to 0.14, and the refresh can
still be skipped using the `-refresh=false` cli flag.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MartiUK/terraform/commits/0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1"},{"sha":"e614fb9aed597252e6ca18244ca779e0d61d3683","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh is expected for destroy

To enable optimization with sparsity, use:

converter.convert()

Note:

3) Not all kernels have been optimized for sparse execution, so the initial benefit will primarily be in the model size on disk.

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

* feat(kuma-cp) send custom strings in health checks

Introducing new field called `tcp` in HealthCheck resource, with
fields `send` and `receive`, which can be provided and will configure
envoy to send provided bytes during tcp health check and expecting
provided bytes in response. Field `receive` expect list of bytes as you
can specify multiple byte blocks. When checking the response,
“fuzzy” matching is performed such that each block must be found, and in
the order specified, but not necessarily contiguous.

More:
https://www.envoyproxy.io/docs/envoy/latest/configuration/upstream/cluster_manager/cluster_hc#config-cluster-manager-cluster-hc

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* feat(kuma-cp) http health checks

Introduced possibility to provide HTTP configuration for health checks,
which will send health checks as HTTP requests.

As internal traffic is mostly using HTTP 2, it's the default protocol
used when health checks are configured to use HTTP. To change that
behaviour you can use `http.use_http1` parameter and set it to true.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) regenerate protobufs for healthchecks

As in master landed PR with protobuf upgrade, I had to regenerate
protbuf related code for health checks, it also involved small changes
in health_check_configurer_test.go file.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) adress comments from CR + more

- Found nasty bug when provided `expectedStatuses` in your health check
  manifest it was generating wrong Int64Range as it should be half
  closed (`start` is inclusive and `end` is exclusive), so it was fixed,
  and the tests reflects this
- Changed some of the properties of the HealthCheck resource to the
  primitive ones (`string`s) and removed logic related to validation if
  the value is provided or empty
- As after protobuf upgrade when unmarshaling our manifests when
  provided empty slices they are becoming `nil`s
- Used `oneof` for `http`/`tcp` blocks in HealthCheck resource and
  removed validation logic which was checking if both of them were not
  provided at the same time

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"79c7e6e677d65979628353eaefe44170d3f2b4b0","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #45457 from rkuester:feature-micro-add-op-fill-pr3

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351196886
Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"79c7e6e677d65979628353eaefe44170d3f2b4b0","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #45457 from rkuester:feature-micro-add-op-fill-pr3

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351196886
Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"026ba5b01344da2f43966367ab8922042933acb6","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"ensure context cancel is never nil

The context used for Stop is more appropriately tied to the lifetime of
the provisioner rather than a call to the ProvisionResource method. In
some cases Stop can be called before ProvisionResource, causing a panic
the provisioner.  Rather than adding nil checks to the CancelFunc call
for Stop, create a base context to use for cancellation with both Stop
and Close methods.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dweomer/terraform/commits/026ba5b01344da2f43966367ab8922042933acb6"},{"sha":"3e224df3794e9f21a015a749e7163f9be3896e64","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"destroy plan with provider config from data","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dweomer/terraform/commits/3e224df3794e9f21a015a749e7163f9be3896e64"},{"sha":"0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh state during a destroy plan

Because the destroy plan only creates the necessary changes for apply to
remove all the resources, it does no reading of resources or data
sources, leading to stale data in the state. In most cases this is not a
problem, but when a provider configuration is using resource values, the
provider may not be able to run correctly during apply. In prior
versions of terraform, the implicit refresh that happened during
`terraform destroy` would update the data sources and remove missing
resources from state as required.

The destroy plan graph has a minimal amount of information, so it is not
feasible to work the reading of resources into the operation without
completely replicating the normal plan graph, and updating the plan
graph and all destroy node implementation is also a considerable amount
of refactoring. Instead, we can run a normal plan which is used to
refresh the state before creating the destroy plan. This brings back
similar behavior to core versions prior to 0.14, and the refresh can
still be skipped using the `-refresh=false` cli flag.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dweomer/terraform/commits/0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1"},{"sha":"e614fb9aed597252e6ca18244ca779e0d61d3683","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh is expected for destroy

These tests were not previously running a refresh, and hence did not

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351196886
Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"2601979e6a3e404aec448b5406442bd3c85f6d9d","author":{"name":"Matthias Bläsing","email":"2733b4844ad39354bd21fd2bca55a8804e19a60d@doppel-helix.eu"},"message":"[NETBEANS-3409] Missing popup menu for sql editor tabs

The Filesystems API compatibility module provides implementations for
Filesystem#getActions for several filesystems. Most filesystem
implementations are covered by the implementation in
AbstractFileSystemCompat, but this does not cover implementations
directly inheriting from Filesystem.

One such filesystem is BinaryFS.

In the SQL Editor the command window function (temp files for SQL
execution) is backed by a file in the SystemFileSystem, which delegates
in the end to BinaryFS:

SystemFileSystem->
  ModuleLayeredFileSystem ->
    BinaryFS

As BinaryFS does not implement getActions and no patch is provided for
this class, an AbstractMethodError is raised.

Instead of bailing out with an Error, the compatibility implementation
now returns an empty array to satisfy the Filesystem#getActions contract.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/apache/netbeans/commits/2601979e6a3e404aec448b5406442bd3c85f6d9d"}]
