Change-Id: Ifa9821e3dc1d4fd15c440da19a7e03d26daaa89e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/c4b65fb31409e3dbd0ad8a33423f86971cc27162"},{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

* feat(kuma-cp) send custom strings in health checks

Introducing new field called `tcp` in HealthCheck resource, with
fields `send` and `receive`, which can be provided and will configure
envoy to send provided bytes during tcp health check and expecting
provided bytes in response. Field `receive` expect list of bytes as you
can specify multiple byte blocks. When checking the response,
“fuzzy” matching is performed such that each block must be found, and in
the order specified, but not necessarily contiguous.

More:
https://www.envoyproxy.io/docs/envoy/latest/configuration/upstream/cluster_manager/cluster_hc#config-cluster-manager-cluster-hc

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* feat(kuma-cp) http health checks

Introduced possibility to provide HTTP configuration for health checks,
which will send health checks as HTTP requests.

As internal traffic is mostly using HTTP 2, it's the default protocol
used when health checks are configured to use HTTP. To change that
behaviour you can use `http.use_http1` parameter and set it to true.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) regenerate protobufs for healthchecks

As in master landed PR with protobuf upgrade, I had to regenerate
protbuf related code for health checks, it also involved small changes
in health_check_configurer_test.go file.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) adress comments from CR + more

- Found nasty bug when provided `expectedStatuses` in your health check
  manifest it was generating wrong Int64Range as it should be half
  closed (`start` is inclusive and `end` is exclusive), so it was fixed,
  and the tests reflects this
- Changed some of the properties of the HealthCheck resource to the
  primitive ones (`string`s) and removed logic related to validation if
  the value is provided or empty
- As after protobuf upgrade when unmarshaling our manifests when
  provided empty slices they are becoming `nil`s
- Used `oneof` for `http`/`tcp` blocks in HealthCheck resource and
  removed validation logic which was checking if both of them were not
  provided at the same time

partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351103206
Change-Id: Ifa9821e3dc1d4fd15c440da19a7e03d26daaa89e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/c4b65fb31409e3dbd0ad8a33423f86971cc27162"},{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YINZHI-keji/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"091856315b2f1c9e968750ecccbade7d5aa4d7db","author":{"name":"A. * feat(kuma-cp) send custom strings in health checks

Introducing new field called `tcp` in HealthCheck resource, with
fields `send` and `receive`, which can be provided and will configure
envoy to send provided bytes during tcp health check and expecting
provided bytes in response. Field `receive` expect list of bytes as you
can specify multiple byte blocks. When checking the response,
“fuzzy” matching is performed such that each block must be found, and in
the order specified, but not necessarily contiguous.

More:
https://www.envoyproxy.io/docs/envoy/latest/configuration/upstream/cluster_manager/cluster_hc#config-cluster-manager-cluster-hc

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* feat(kuma-cp) http health checks

Introduced possibility to provide HTTP configuration for health checks,
which will send health checks as HTTP requests.

As internal traffic is mostly using HTTP 2, it's the default protocol
used when health checks are configured to use HTTP. To change that
behaviour you can use `http.use_http1` parameter and set it to true.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) regenerate protobufs for healthchecks

As in master landed PR with protobuf upgrade, I had to regenerate
protbuf related code for health checks, it also involved small changes
in health_check_configurer_test.go file.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) adress comments from CR + more

- Found nasty bug when provided `expectedStatuses` in your health check
  manifest it was generating wrong Int64Range as it should be half
  closed (`start` is inclusive and `end` is exclusive), so it was fixed,
  and the tests reflects this
- Changed some of the properties of the HealthCheck resource to the
  primitive ones (`string`s) and removed logic related to validation if
  the value is provided or empty
- As after protobuf upgrade when unmarshaling our manifests when
  provided empty slices they are becoming `nil`s
- Used `oneof` for `http`/`tcp` blocks in HealthCheck resource and
  removed validation logic which was checking if both of them were not
  provided at the same time

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351196886
Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/joshrose/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

Signed-off-by: Nikolay Nikolaev <nikolay.nikolaev@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jewertow/kuma/commits/3e43e3cd703021e486fca8eb1016e8f4689c8082"},{"sha":"a0b6b2cf47781bd3f234239e0c5082e2e0cf0f41","author":{"name":"Bart Smykla","email":"1510bcc82b444bd3d94fed33ba1fa2e72fc0e429@smykla.com"},"message":"feat(kuma-cp) http health checks + send custom strings in tcp health checks (#1261)

* feat(kuma-cp) send custom strings in health checks

Introducing new field called `tcp` in HealthCheck resource, with
fields `send` and `receive`, which can be provided and will configure
envoy to send provided bytes during tcp health check and expecting
provided bytes in response. Field `receive` expect list of bytes as you
can specify multiple byte blocks. When checking the response,
“fuzzy” matching is performed such that each block must be found, and in
the order specified, but not necessarily contiguous.

More:
https://www.envoyproxy.io/docs/envoy/latest/configuration/upstream/cluster_manager/cluster_hc#config-cluster-manager-cluster-hc

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* feat(kuma-cp) http health checks

Introduced possibility to provide HTTP configuration for health checks,
which will send health checks as HTTP requests.

As internal traffic is mostly using HTTP 2, it's the default protocol
used when health checks are configured to use HTTP. To change that
behaviour you can use `http.use_http1` parameter and set it to true.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) regenerate protobufs for healthchecks

As in master landed PR with protobuf upgrade, I had to regenerate
protbuf related code for health checks, it also involved small changes
in health_check_configurer_test.go file.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) adress comments from CR + more

- Found nasty bug when provided `expectedStatuses` in your health check
  manifest it was generating wrong Int64Range as it should be half
  closed (`start` is inclusive and `end` is exclusive), so it was fixed,
  and the tests reflects this
- Changed some of the properties of the HealthCheck resource to the
  primitive ones (`string`s) and removed logic related to validation if
  the value is provided or empty
- As after protobuf upgrade when unmarshaling our manifests when
  provided empty slices they are becoming `nil`s
- Used `oneof` for `http`/`tcp` blocks in HealthCheck resource and
  removed validation logic which was checking if both of them were not
  provided at the same time

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/joshrose/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"79c7e6e677d65979628353eaefe44170d3f2b4b0","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #45457 from rkuester:feature-micro-add-op-fill-pr3

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351196886
Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"026ba5b01344da2f43966367ab8922042933acb6","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"ensure context cancel is never nil

The context used for Stop is more appropriately tied to the lifetime of
the provisioner rather than a call to the ProvisionResource method. In
some cases Stop can be called before ProvisionResource, causing a panic
the provisioner.  Rather than adding nil checks to the CancelFunc call
for Stop, create a base context to use for cancellation with both Stop
and Close methods.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/avmi/terraform/commits/026ba5b01344da2f43966367ab8922042933acb6"},{"sha":"3e224df3794e9f21a015a749e7163f9be3896e64","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"destroy plan with provider config from data","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/avmi/terraform/commits/3e224df3794e9f21a015a749e7163f9be3896e64"},{"sha":"0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh state during a destroy plan

Because the destroy plan only creates the necessary changes for apply to
remove all the resources, it does no reading of resources or data
sources, leading to stale data in the state. In most cases this is not a
problem, but when a provider configuration is using resource values, the
provider may not be able to run correctly during apply. In prior
versions of terraform, the implicit refresh that happened during
`terraform destroy` would update the data sources and remove missing
resources from state as required.

The destroy plan graph has a minimal amount of information, so it is not
feasible to work the reading of resources into the operation without
completely replicating the normal plan graph, and updating the plan
graph and all destroy node implementation is also a considerable amount
of refactoring. Instead, we can run a normal plan which is used to
refresh the state before creating the destroy plan. This brings back
similar behavior to core versions prior to 0.14, and the refresh can
still be skipped using the `-refresh=false` cli flag.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/avmi/terraform/commits/0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1"},{"sha":"e614fb9aed597252e6ca18244ca779e0d61d3683","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh is expected for destroy

When user supplies env-vars through kumactl, they are being added to the default list of env-vars instead of replacing them.
This fix makes sure the supplied env-vars get overridden properly if the env-var exists in default list otherwise they are added to the list.

* Create new template in _helpers.tpl and use it to generate env-vars in cp-deployment.yaml
* Update helmtemplates_vfsdata.go, since cp-deployment.yaml changed
* Update install-control-plane test cases, since generation of env-vars changed
* Add new test case in install-control-plane to test the fix

Fix #1273

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351196886
Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

[{"sha":"dff3c8a47a24b27f3e490f15f4de90743efc7ecf","author":{"name":"YoungSeok Yoon","email":"2194426b8aa8a9a28fe32e8dd1dad861dde7918b@google.com"},"message":"Fix iOS static framework link error by using custom object file extractor

With the bazel version update from 3.1.0 to 3.7.2, the object file hash values
are no longer added when their names are unique within an objc_library. See:
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/11846
* https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11958

However, object name collision can still happen when there is a source code with
the same basename in a transitive dependency tree. Normally there is no problem
with this, but this had an unfortunate interaction with the symbol hiding script
we use for building the iOS static framework. That is, when an archive file (.a)
contains more than one object file with the same name, the 'ar -x' command
executed as part of the symbol hiding script would overwrite the conflicting
object file, causing the overwritten object file to be not included in the final
static framework.

This was causing a link error at CocoaPods lint step, as it had some missing
function definitions. This is now fixed by using a custom extraction script
written in Python, which gracefully handles the object file name collision.

This also fixes a previously existed race condition when the symbol hiding
script is run in parallel for multiple static framework targets, by using
separate temporary directories while extracting the object files.

Verified that this fix works with CocoaPods lint.

Signed-off-by: Nikolay Nikolaev <nikolay.nikolaev@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jewertow/kuma/commits/3e43e3cd703021e486fca8eb1016e8f4689c8082"},{"sha":"a0b6b2cf47781bd3f234239e0c5082e2e0cf0f41","author":{"name":"Bart Smykla","email":"1510bcc82b444bd3d94fed33ba1fa2e72fc0e429@smykla.com"},"message":"feat(kuma-cp) http health checks + send custom strings in tcp health checks (#1261)

* feat(kuma-cp) send custom strings in health checks

Introducing new field called `tcp` in HealthCheck resource, with
fields `send` and `receive`, which can be provided and will configure
envoy to send provided bytes during tcp health check and expecting
provided bytes in response. Field `receive` expect list of bytes as you
can specify multiple byte blocks. When checking the response,
“fuzzy” matching is performed such that each block must be found, and in
the order specified, but not necessarily contiguous.

More:
https://www.envoyproxy.io/docs/envoy/latest/configuration/upstream/cluster_manager/cluster_hc#config-cluster-manager-cluster-hc

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* feat(kuma-cp) http health checks

Introduced possibility to provide HTTP configuration for health checks,
which will send health checks as HTTP requests.

As internal traffic is mostly using HTTP 2, it's the default protocol
used when health checks are configured to use HTTP. To change that
behaviour you can use `http.use_http1` parameter and set it to true.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) regenerate protobufs for healthchecks

As in master landed PR with protobuf upgrade, I had to regenerate
protbuf related code for health checks, it also involved small changes
in health_check_configurer_test.go file.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) adress comments from CR + more

- Found nasty bug when provided `expectedStatuses` in your health check
  manifest it was generating wrong Int64Range as it should be half
  closed (`start` is inclusive and `end` is exclusive), so it was fixed,
  and the tests reflects this
- Changed some of the properties of the HealthCheck resource to the
  primitive ones (`string`s) and removed logic related to validation if
  the value is provided or empty
- As after protobuf upgrade when unmarshaling our manifests when
  provided empty slices they are becoming `nil`s
- Used `oneof` for `http`/`tcp` blocks in HealthCheck resource and
  removed validation logic which was checking if both of them were not
  provided at the same time

Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.
